<section class="project-section">
  <div class="container">

    <div class="problem-solution">
      <div class="problem-solution-col">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">The Problem</div>
        <p>Most intro psych courses deliver content passively, and OER materials alone don't close equity gaps or address the full scope of what students need. Many students arrive underprepared, and many instructors — particularly adjuncts — have limited time to build their own course materials from scratch.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-solution-col">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">The Solution</div>
        <p>A fully scaffolded courseware system built around the APA Guidelines for the Undergraduate Psychology Major, with 2,700+ assessments, in-class activities, complete instructor guides, and ongoing data-driven updates.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>Lumen Learning's Introductory Psychology course is now the highest-enrolled non-math course on the platform, with over 200,000 students served. It started as an OER adaptation of OpenStax Psychology content and has grown through three platform generations over eight-plus years into a full courseware system with original content, quizzes, instructor-ready activities, and regular updates.</p>

    <p>I built and continue to maintain all 16 modules. Each one follows a consistent structure: Readiness Check, Background You'll Need, Learn It content, embedded "Try It" practice questions, Apply It activities, Self-Check quizzes, review materials on a "Get Stronger" page, and a Summative Quiz. That predictability matters. Students quickly understand what's expected, and instructors can navigate the course without a learning curve.</p>

    <p>This course, like the others I worked on, required extensive preliminary research and preparation. Luckily, this one at least has some foundational materials to work from (OpenStax and Noba Psychology). Other courses, like Lifespan Development, Psychopathology, and English Composition, were authored entirely from scratch without any pre-existing materials. For Intro Psych, analysis and research led me to build the course around the APA Guidelines for the Undergraduate Psychology Major (Version 3.0). I wove the seven APA Integrative Themes throughout, so students encounter those ideas in context rather than as add-ons at the end of a chapter.</p>

    <figure class="project-figure">
      <img src="/images/projects/psych/slide-04.png" alt="Course approach slide showing APA 7 Integrative Themes" />
    </figure>

    <div class="section-eyebrow">Content Development</div>

    <p>I led the content development with a team of subject matter experts, typically between 6 and 10 per course. On this project, I especially enjoyed working with Patrick Carroll at the University of Texas at Austin, who helped create "Psych in Real Life" features and Readiness Check examples that give students meaningful applications of the content. Pat helped me think more creatively about pulling research examples into the course and making them more digestible for students. I love the pieces we added about the reproducibility crisis in psychology, applications of conditioning, how research is conducted with infants, and how someone might overcome anxiety related to public speaking. Jessica Traylor at Gordon State College also contributed significantly, especially in building interactive components to support student engagement. This fit with our broader focus on making psychology readable, relatable, and culturally grounded. We added new sections to address a more nuanced and complete history of psychology, its WEIRD bias (western, educated, industrialized, rich, and democratic) in psychological research, and wove references to culturally competent practice throughout the course.</p>

    <blockquote class="callout-quote">
      <p>"Working with Wendy from Lumen was amazing! Besides being a content expert, she is an amazing coach. If you have the opportunity to work with her on anything, I would highly recommend it."</p>
      <cite>— Jessica Traylor, Psychology Instructor and Subject Matter Expert</cite>
    </blockquote>

    <div class="section-eyebrow">Supporting Instructors</div>

    <p>Because many Intro Psych instructors are adjuncts with limited prep time, I put real work into the instructor side of the course. Supporting instructors through the teaching process has been an essential goal and focus of mine since starting at Lumen, so I was thrilled with the changes in Lumen One that enabled even more instructor support. In addition to providing a full engagement center with data about each student, we support instructors with in-class activities, discussions, assignments, and relevant evidence-based teaching practices. Every module includes a complete Instructor Guide with learning outcomes, module summaries, and detailed activity notes that explain not just how to run an activity but why. Each module also comes with a ready-to-use PowerPoint deck.</p>

    <figure class="project-figure">
      <img src="/images/projects/psych/slide-15.png" alt="Instructor Guides with Module 8 detail" />
    </figure>

    <div class="section-eyebrow">Continuous Improvement</div>

    <p>After completing the course build, we continue to invest time and energy in revisions and improvements. We use data on student performance across learning outcomes to make continuous improvements to the assessments, content, and activities. Recent update cycles added new research on topics like psychedelic-assisted therapy, the replication crisis, the gut-brain connection, and AI in decision-making. New classroom activities include Memory Championships (students compete using evidence-based memory strategies), a Happiness Lab (based on Berkeley's Greater Good Science Center research), and AI Study Partner (students learn to use AI as a personalized study tool).</p>

    <p>I also had the chance to teach with this course at Davidson College. Teaching from the materials directly surfaced small friction points that aren't always visible during development, and several updates came directly out of that experience.</p>

    <p>This course remains the project I'm most proud of, not because it's finished, but because after all these years it keeps getting better.</p>

